replies.bodyText:
@qqmyers as of the commit you added I don't think the case of a PID that can't be found makes sense. Below you can see that when a PID exists, you get a nice "findable" message but when you add some characters to the end of the PID such that it doesn't exist, you get a message saying "API endpoint does not exist on this server" which doesn't make sense:
beamish:dataverse pdurbin$ export PID=doi:10.70122/FK2/9BXT5O
beamish:dataverse pdurbin$ 
beamish:dataverse pdurbin$ curl -s -H "X-Dataverse-key:$API_TOKEN" $SERVER_URL/api/pids?persistentId=$PID | jq .
{
  "status": "OK",
  "data": {
    "id": "10.70122/fk2/9bxt5o",
    "state": "findable"
  }
}
beamish:dataverse pdurbin$ export PID=doi:10.70122/FK2/9BXT5Ozzz
beamish:dataverse pdurbin$ 
beamish:dataverse pdurbin$ curl -s -H "X-Dataverse-key:$API_TOKEN" $SERVER_URL/api/pids?persistentId=$PID | jq .
{
  "status": "ERROR",
  "code": 404,
  "message": "API endpoint does not exist on this server. Please check your code for typos, or consult our API guide at http://guides.dataverse.org.",
  "requestUrl": "http://localhost:8080/api/v1/pids?persistentId=doi:10.70122/FK2/9BXT5Ozzz",
  "requestMethod": "GET"
}
beamish:dataverse pdurbin$
